message: TODAY is the last day to submit your photos to have them be featured on my Facebook page. Send them to wi3photos@mail.house.gov

I am glad my Republican colleagues listened to the people and decided not to dismantle the Office of Congressional Ethics. At a time when Wisconsinites have lost trust in Washington further weakening transparency and accountability for members of Congress is not the way to rebuild that trust. This will always be the People‚Äôs House.   https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/03/house-republicans-just-did-something-very-very-dumb/?utm_term=.fa2b768d2279
With President Obama for his last visit to Capitol Hill during his Presidency. Much was accomplished under his leadership, more challenges still await with a new administration.

Wisconsinites can not afford to go back to a time when people with pre-existing conditions, women, and seniors did not have acces to affordable, quality health care.   Share your story about how the Affordable Care Act has impacted you,
Last week I enjoyed talking with student leaders from universities across Wisconsin about how we can work together to make college more affordable and make sure all students feel safe on campus.

I have long said that the best ideas for bills come directly from Wisconsinites and the Honoring Our Heroes Act is a great example of that. I am proud to introduce a bill to make sure that no other family is denied their loved ones service medals simply because of an arbitrary rule. Read more about Tari's story here:

I know many people, myself included, have been deeply concerned about Russian interference in our 2016 election. If you want to know more I encourage you to read the unclassified report our intelligence agencies presented to President Obama and President-Elect Trump.   Read the report here: https://www.dni.gov/files/documents/ICA_2017_01.pdf
I had a great time Skyping with Mr. Beckstrom's Economics class at Onalaska High School today.  I always enjoy the opportunity to speak with the future leaders of tomorrow!

I am deeply skeptical of President-elect Trump‚Äôs appointment of David Friedman as ambassador to Israel.  Friedman supports moving the US embassy to Jerusalem, he is pro-settlement, and he opposes Palestinian statehood.  None of these positions help promote peace, nor do they reflect long-standing US policy.
WHAT A GAME!! #gopackgo

Ms. DeVos‚Äô track record of taking money away from public education and into private and for-profit education and her lack of classroom and administrative experience is deeply concerning. We need to make sure we have a Secretary of Education who understands the importance of providing our schools and teachers the resources they need to make sure our children receive a quality education.

Thank you President Obama for your work over the last 8 years to grow the economy, provide affordable health care, and keep our country safe. You are leaving us with a record 75 consecutive months of private sector job growth.   My family, the people of Wisconsin, and all Americans are grateful for your service. #thanksobama

The strongest voice in our democracy should be yours, not special interest groups and super-PACs.  On the seventh anniversary of the Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission ruling, join me in calling for an end to big money in politics.

Our veterans have sacrificed so much for our country, and the last thing that should be done is to make them have to wait longer to receive the care they have earned and deserve. This is a shameful first act for the new administration.    Read more: http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/24/trump-hiring-freeze-includes-veterans-affairs/96999464/

On Holocaust Memorial Day, we remember and mourn the atrocious murder of over 6 million Jewish people, including 1.5 million children. We will never forget those who perished because of hateful rhetoric and intolerance, and will always work together to create a more peaceful and accepting world.

It‚Äôs time that we put Wisconsinites before partisanship and special interests. While today was a good step, we need to put an independent bipartisan redistricting commission in place to ensure people pick their representatives not the other way around.   Check out more on my legislation to do this here: https://kind.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-ron-kind-cosponsors-bipartisan-bill-reform-redistricting-0

Instead of helping keep our country safe, President Trump's executive order will jeopardize our national security by giving ISIS and other terror groups another recruitment tool and making it harder for our allies in Muslim nations to work with us on counter-terrorism operations. I am calling on President Trump to immediately suspend his Executive Order.  Read my full statement here: kind.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-kind-s-statement-president-trump-s-immigration-executive-order

The Wisconsin beer industry not only produces the best beer in the world, but it also creates jobs and grows the local economy in communities across central and western Wisconsin. I am proud to introduce a bipartisan bill to help Wisconsin brewers - large and small, tap into new markets and create good-paying jobs here in Wisconsin.  Read more here: https://www.yahoo.com/news/beer-institute-praises-introduction-craft-beverage-modernization-tax-163500929.html

Over the past decade, economic growth has focused on the East Coast and the West Coast and left the Heartland behind. It is time we take steps to fix this problem.Today, I introduced a bipartisan bill to level the playing field for our Wisconsin communities and help create good-paying jobs where we need them the most.
Today's decision was an important step in the right direction, but we must remain vigilant. I will continue to stand against any attempt to discriminate against people based on their religion.

It was great to stop by the Menomonie Fire Department to see the Department's new Jaws of Life, which was purchased with grant money from an Assistance to Firefighters Grant. Our firefighters deserve the best technology and equipment we can provide.
Matt Brigson of Holmen was recently honored as the 2016 AFGE Law Enforcement Officer of the Year, doing both Wisconsin and  Union Local 1882 AFGE proud. Congratulations on the honor, Matt!

During Black History Month, I always think of La Crosse native, George Poage. George was the first African-American athlete to win a medal at the Olympic games in 1904.    If you're in the La Crosse area, be sure to check out Poage Park and the new bronze statue of George.

Today, during National Court Reporter's Week, I recognized our nation's Court Reporters for the great work they do in our courts and communities. I'd like to wish my favorite court reporter - my wife, Tawni - a happy Court Reporters Week, and a happy Valentine's day, too!

Today, in a meeting with students and leaders from Wisconsin Technical Colleges I unveiled my Higher Education Action Plan. My plan helps Wisconsin students prepare for college, increases affordability, and creates job opportunities.
Today, Team Kind joined American Legion leaders for a briefing with VA Tomah director Victoria Brahm. Great discussion on how we can work together to best serve our Wisconsin veterans.
I hope you can join me for a Listening Session in La Crosse next Wednesday, February 22nd at 3:00 p.m.  Stop by the American Legion, Post 52 to share your concerns and ask questions.
"We are not enemies, but friends. We must not be enemies. Though passion may have strained, it must not break our bonds of affection." ~ President Abraham Lincoln   Happy Presidents' Day!
I hope you can join me tomorrow at 3:00pm for a Listening Session at the American Legion, Post 52 in La Crosse. Stop by to share your concerns and ask questions.

I'm happy to welcome Dr Donn Dexter from Eau Claire as my guest to President Trump's first Address to Congress. Let's all work to make quality healthcare affordable for all Americans.
Looks like there was a turkey jam in Eau Claire. Only in Wisconsin!   This is just more proof that our wild turkey reintroduction program is working.

Fun Fact of the Day: This week in 1872 Yellowstone National Park was established.   Some of my favorite memories are the family trips we have taken to explore our national treasures. As co-chair of the National Parks Caucus, I will work to make sure our National Parks are preserved and protected for future generations.

Today in Eau Claire, I thanked Boua Chao Xiong for his 26 years of service to the Eau Claire Fire Department. Boua Chao was a firetruck driver and engineer, and was also the first Hmong firefighter in America.

Today the House Ways and Means Committee is pushing forward with a bill to repeal the ACA that will put Medicare in jeopardy, raise insurance premiums for Wisconsinites, jeopardize access to care in rural areas, result in loss of coverage for thousands of people, and give the wealthiest citizens an average yearly tax cut of around $195,000. Unacceptable!   I am proud to be here fighting to make sure Wisconsinites don't #PayMoreForLess

I called for assurances from Congressional Republican's that their health care plan will be completely paid for, will not add to the national debt, and won't make Wisconsinites lose coverage. They could not guarantee that.

Jessie, a mom from Amherst, has a six-year-old daughter with a heart condition. The ACA gave her the certainty that her daughter isn‚Äôt denied insurance because of a pre-existing condition. However, with the repeal of the ACA, there is an open question to whether or not that will continue to be the case, and if it is whether the cost will skyrocket.  "I have enough worries hanging over my head," Jessie said. "The last thing I should be worried about is Congress rolling back a policy my daughter and I depend on."

Jenny‚Äôs daughter had cancer when she was 10. She is 14 now and cancer free, but has undergone many surgeries, scans and high medication costs. She will continue to be high risk and incur medical expenses for the rest of her life. A lifetime max limit on insurance payout concerns Jenny every day.  ‚ÄúI am constantly thinking about what her future looks like if she has a reoccurrence.‚Äù Jenny said.

Bonnie worked 40 hours a week from the age of 17 to 66, and raised two children alone, without any minimum child support.  "It should now be my time now," Bonnie said. "But instead I'm worried about being able to afford health care for myself." #PayMoreForLess

Today‚Äôs report from the Congressional Budget Office (CBO), the nonpartisan referee responsible for laying out the impact of policies, raises serious red flags about the Congressional Republicans Health Bill. CBO findings prove that their bill results in skyrocketing insurance premiums for older Wisconsinites and millions losing health care coverage.
Today we are holding are hearing to hear directly from health care experts on the impacts of the Congressional Republican Health Bill. Watch the hearing below.

The Trump Administration‚Äôs 2018 budget blueprint would have a devastating impact on rural Wisconsin. Instead of supporting programs that create jobs and grow our rural Wisconsin communities it guts the programs they depend on.
The best way to ring in another 29th birthday is with a Logan Rangers and Green Bay Packers themed cake! Ì†ºÌøà
Happy National Agriculture Day! Thank you to our hardworking farmers for all of your contributions to Western and Central Wisconsin. #AgDay2017 #thankafarmer

Wisconsinites know that the disastrous Congressional Republican Health Bill is a bad deal for them. My office has taken 1557 calls and emails urging me to oppose the bill and only 18 in support of it.
COMING SOON: I am going to be speaking on the House Floor about why the #PayMoreForLess bill is a bad deal for Wisconsinites.Watch the debate below.

It is clear that House Republican leadership was trying to force a bad bill. Instead of rushing forward a bill, without any hearings, I hope they use this time to recognize what works in healthcare and work in a bipartisan manner to fix what doesn‚Äôt and lower healthcare costs for all Americans.
Over his last four years as a University of Wisconsin-Madison Badger Bronson Koenig has made La Crosse proud!

Wisconsin Wisdom: Did you know that Wisconsin was the first state to ratify the 19th Amendment, granting American women the right to vote?   During Women's History Month, we remember Ada James, a Richland Center native, suffragist, social worker, and reformer. After the suffrage battle was won in 1920, Ada spent her life focused on finding homes for underprivileged children in Wisconsin.

Today, I am voting against a bill that could result in the websites you visit, apps you use, the content of your emails, web search history, and your private health and financial information being sold to corporations without your permission.   This bill is outrageous! Wisconsinites have a right to protect their private information and not have corporations sell it without their knowledge or permission.

I am calling on the Governor to end his ideological war on the Affordable Care Act and accept federal funding to expand BadgerCare for Wisconsin‚Äôs disabled, children, and seniors. Wisconsin has already missed out on the chance to save over $690 million and ensure health care coverage for thousands of Wisconsinites.  More here: https://kind.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/rep-kind-calls-governor-walker-put-wisconsinites-first-and-expand

Thanks to everyone who took time out of their Saturday to attend my Eau Claire listening session. I appreciated hearing your concerns and answering your questions.   If you weren't able to make it you can always call my office at 608-782-2558 or visit kind.house.gov to send me an email.

Listening to the great John Lewis, my colleague in Congress, describe his work with Martin Luther King Jr and what he was doing on this day when MLK was assassinated. The fight for justice and equality marches on.

It was great to spend time with a group of Arcadia High School juniors last week at the steps of the Capitol.  I always enjoy sharing my story and encouraging our young people to go into public service.

Once again Governor Scott Walker misses the point. By doubling down and refusing to accept BadgerCare expansion he continues to ignore what is best for Wisconsin taxpayers and Wisconsin families in favor of partisan politics.
Thanks to all the high school students who submitted their work! I am always impressed by the talent and creativity of Wisconsinites.
This afternoon I had a productive roundtable discussion with Eau Claire business leaders about creating jobs, reforming the tax code, and growing the Wisconsin economy.

National Park Service Week is April 15-23. In the week ahead, I look forward to sharing my favorite National Park Service photos, and hope to see you share your favorite NPS memories, too! Share yours by posting a photo to my Facebook, or tagging me in your favorite memory.

Some of my favorite memories with my family were made on trips to National Parks.  Here's a photo of my family exploring Rocky Mountain National Park back in 2008. Be sure to share your favorite #NPS photo on my wall during #NationalParkWeek!

Did you know that all National Park Service sites that charge an entrance fee will offer free admission to everyone this weekend?  Finding your Park is a great way to spend your #EarthDay2017 weekend! And thanks to everyone that has shared your favorite #NPS memory.  Here's a photo of Tawni, the boys and me exploring the Grand Canyon in 2013.

Gaylord Nelson, Wisconsinite and founder of Earth Day once said:   "Our goal is not just an environment of clean air and water and scenic beauty. The objective is an environment of decency, quality and mutual respect for all other human beings and all other living creatures."  These are powerful words, and a reminder of the importance of respecting our neighbors and our land. Since the boys were young, Tawni and I have shared the importance of our natural resources with them. Some of our best memories come from family trips to State and National Parks.  As a Co-Chair of the National Parks Caucus, I have worked hard to ensure our future generations can celebrate the beauty of America, and continue to be inspired by nature, just like my boys have throughout the years. I hope you take the time today to explore a park, the bluffs, or even your own backyard. Western and central Wisconsin is filled with beautiful places to celebrate Earth Day, and it's our job to protect the land for years to come.

It's all hands on deck, with a May 1st deadline approaching.  I am calling on the Trump Administration to work with Wisconsin dairy farmers to create a plan for addressing the immediate and long-term impact of the Grassland Dairy decision and for ending the unfair trade practices at the root of the current problem.   http://www.wisfarmer.com/story/news/2017/04/25/kind-calls-perdue-create-plan-helping-farmers/100903454/
My favorite part of my recent trip to talk with our NATO allies was having the opportunity to thank Wisconsin service members for serving overseas and talk with them about their experiences.
On #WorkersMemorialDay, we remember and honor those that have died while working, and continue the fight for a healthy and safe workplace for everyone.
Small Business Week is April 30-May 6, 2017.  What's your favorite small business in western or central Wisconsin?

It is clear that House Republican leadership is trying to force a bad bill. Instead of moving forward legislation, that will negatively impact the lives of thousands of Wisconsinites, we need to recognize what works in healthcare, fix what doesn‚Äôt, and seek to lower healthcare costs for all Americans

The budget needs to work for rural America, not just the coasts. I am pleased that the bipartisan funding bill supports many programs Wisconsinites depend on. We worked hard to make sure the bill helps keep our communities safe, strengthen our Wisconsin economy, provide assistance to people seeking employment, and support local water projects.

The Congressional Republican healthcare plan is disastrous for Wisconsinites.  Their bill takes away critical protections for people with pre-existing conditions, leads to skyrocketing premiums for older Wisconsinites, and puts Medicare four years closer to going bankrupt. I can‚Äôt support a bill that would make Wisconsinites #PayMoreForLess
You can watch the debate on the Congressional Republican Health Care bill below.

Just voted NO on the disastrous Congressional Republican Health Care Bill. Thank you to the thousands of Wisconsinites who reached out opposed to the bill, while it sadly passed the House today we must keep fighting to make sure it does not become law.
On National Teacher Day, we celebrate and thank the educators that changed our lives and helped us become who we are today.  Be sure to thank your teachers today - and every day! #ThankaTeacher

I hope and pray today's rash decision by President Trump to fire FBI Director James Comey had nothing to do with the FBI's independent investigation into Russian interference and possible collusion of Trump associates with Russia during the 2016 election. I call on congressional leadership to schedule hearings so we can get to the bottom of this.

Thank you to everyone in western and central Wisconsin that joined me at my recent listening sessions. Hearing from Wisconsinites about the issues that matter most to them is my favorite part of this job.
Western and central Wisconsin is home to some of the best outdoor recreation, beautiful landscapes and fun festivals.  What's your favorite thing to do in Wisconsin?   #NationalTravelandTourismWeek

Today, during Police Week I had the honor of speaking at the La Crosse County Law Enforcement Memorial Ceremony. We remembered the officers in Wisconsin that sacrificed their lives to keep our communities safe and thanked our officers for their service.

I am deeply disturbed that President Trump made the careless decision to share classified information with Russian officials. The Administration needs to inform the House and Senate Intelligence Committees the full nature of the information revealed and any damage it may cause. Our intelligence officers and allies go to great lengths to make sure any and all threats to the United States are addressed, and this careless sharing of information puts their mission and the safety of our country at risk.

With far too many Wisconsin men and women paying their student loans but not able to get ahead because of high interest rates, it is time to take action and allow people to refinance their student loans. I was proud to introduce the Bank on Students Emergency Loan Refinancing Act.

Tornado and flood warnings have been issued in counties across western Wisconsin. Take shelter from the storm in an underground shelter, basement or safe room, away from windows.   http://www.wxow.com/story/35450514/2017/05/17/more-severe-weather-potential-today#

My thoughts and prayers are with the victims of the senseless and horrific bombing in Manchester and their families.

Instead of supporting programs that partner with local communities to create jobs and grow our rural Wisconsin economy the Administration‚Äôs budget guts the programs they depend on.   There is nothing fiscally responsible about making drastic cuts to programs like the Rural Economic Development and Community Development Block grant programs to pay for outdated military equipment that even our Generals have said they don‚Äôt need.
Today's CBO report further proves that the Congressional Republican Health Care bill is a bad deal for rural Wisconsinites.
As we celebrate Memorial Day across western and central Wisconsin, we remember and honor the soldiers who have sacrificed everything to keep us safe and protect our freedom.
I was honored to speak during a Memorial Day service at Owen Park in Eau Claire, WI. God bless our fallen heroes and take them into his care.

I'm looking forward to showing Rep. Cheri Bustos around southern Wisconsin!  We'll be meeting with local residents, farmers, and small business owners across Grant County to listen to their concerns and share how we are working to level the playing field for rural America. If you're in Platteville, Lancaster or Fennimore, be sure to say hello!
I had a great day showing  Rep. Cheri Bustos around Grant County. Thanks to everyone who took time out of their day to talk with us about how we can partner to grow the rural economy and create jobs.

The world looks to the United States as a leader, and today‚Äôs decision by President Trump to leave the #ParisAgreement puts our standing in the world at risk. We must always make sure the rules work for our country, but walking away from the table endangers the planet for future generations and leaves US workers, farmers, and businesses less competitive.

Thanks to Danielle Benden and Ernie Boszhardt for helping uncover a piece of Driftless area history. If you find yourself in Trempealeau this summer, be sure to check out Little Bluffs Trail and learn more about Wisconsin's amazing past!

No better way to start off your Saturday or Sunday than a Wisconsin Dairy Breakfast!  It's a great way to support your local farmers, and fun for the whole family.   Be sure to check out the Dairy Days of Summer (link below) to find a dairy breakfast near you.   www.dairydaysofsummer.com

Each year I am able to nominate outstanding students from western and central Wisconsin to become our military leaders of the future, and I‚Äôm looking forward to meeting this year‚Äôs applicants.  Nomination applications are now available. If you have any questions or would like more information, please call my Eau Claire office - (715) 831-9214, or visit the link below: http://bit.ly/2sUkjCI

Hope everyone in Portage County is staying safe following the severe storms last night. If you experienced damage to your home or property please call Portage County Emergency Management at 715-343-6200.

Congratulations to the Chippewa Valley Technical College for receiving a Smart Manufacturing and Resources for Transforming the Future (SMART Future) grant totaling nearly $900,000! I look forward to seeing how CVTC will use the grant money to teach young people the skills needed to get good paying jobs here in central and western Wisconsin.   http://bit.ly/2rWswI4

To ensure that our VA facilities are giving Wisconsin veterans the care they have earned and deserve it is critical that there is increased accountability and protections for whistleblowers. Proud to vote for this bipartisan bill.   http://www.npr.org/2017/06/13/531810565/congress-passes-bill-to-increase-accountability-among-va-employees

Today‚Äôs attack at the Congressional baseball practice is yet another tragic and senseless shooting here in America, this time targeted at members of Congress. My thoughts and prayers are with my colleagues, their aides, and the brave Capitol Police who were injured.   I especially want to thank the Capitol Police officers who demonstrated incredible courage, and by their quick action saved lives.

During June Dairy Days I have had the privilege of talking with many dairy farmers and their families, and in each conversation they have emphasized how challenging the past few years have been for them. I worked hard to create a plan to fix some of the problems Wisconsin dairy farmers face, and secure the future of Wisconsin dairy.   Read the plan here:  http://bit.ly/2s6tPEn

Wisconsin milk and cheese are the best in the world, yet many countries still limit dairy imports from the United States, and create policies that hurt our dairy farmers here at home.  I am working hard to open new markets for our farmers to sell their products.   Read more about my comprehensive plan to secure Wisconsin dairy here: http://bit.ly/2s6tPEn

Thank you to the Gerke and Houser families for hosting the La Crosse County dairy breakfast this past weekend.  Tawni and I enjoyed touring the farm, and getting our fill of pancakes, Wisconsin milk, and ice cream!

Today‚Äôs decision by Anthem Health Insurance to stop offering insurance in Wisconsin, due in large part to continual changes and uncertainty in federal operations, rules and guidance, shows exactly what is at stake if the Administration and Congressional Republicans continue to play political games with Wisconsinites‚Äô health care. The hundreds of Wisconsinites who are losing their health care because of this decision deserve better. Instead of increasing uncertainty or pushing forward with a misguided health care bill, we need to recognize what works in healthcare, fix what doesn‚Äôt, and seek to lower healthcare costs for all Americans.

Thanks to Authenticom for taking some time to show me around your La Crosse offices last week. Very impressive and innovative local business that is creating jobs and contributing to the La Crosse economy. I look forward to continuing to work with you to make sure we level the playing field for Wisconsin small businesses.

The bill Senate Republicans introduced today is not a health care bill but a large tax cut bill for the wealthy and powerful special interests at the expense of affordable, quality health care for Wisconsin families and seniors. In addition, it cuts funding to combat the opioid epidemic by billions of dollars. Unacceptable!

As I travel through Western and Central Wisconsin during June Dairy month, I have been talking with Wisconsin dairy farmers about the struggles they are facing and how we can work together to make sure our strong farming tradition is preserved. As USDA Secretary Perdue and Ambassador Lighthizer begin renegotiating our new trade policies with Canada I am strongly encouraging them to come to Wisconsin and hear directly from the dairy farmers about what is working and not working for their farms. Read the letter here: http://bit.ly/2tXz6MH

Today‚Äôs report from the Congressional Budget Office, the nonpartisan referee responsible for laying out the impact of policies, continues to prove that Congressional Republicans are more interested in giving tax cuts to the wealthy and powerful special interests than protecting Medicare and access to quality, affordable health care for Wisconsin families, seniors, and veterans.

I hope that the lesson Senate Republicans take away from today is that it is time to stop pushing this deeply unpopular and misguided "health care" bill.   Instead, we need to recognize what works in healthcare, fix what doesn‚Äôt, and seek to lower healthcare costs for all Americans.

Wisconsin manufacturers are economic drivers in our local communities.  I am proud to introduce the "Invest and Manufacture in America Act" - a bill that will help manufacturers innovate and create jobs where we need them most: western and central Wisconsin.

Today, I joined Emily Sedgwick, from La Farge, to check out the place in the US Capitol where her winning artwork ‚ÄúMy Father‚Äôs Shoes" will be displayed for the next year. Be sure to check it out if you visit DC. Congrats Emily!
I wish everyone in central and western Wisconsin a Happy Independence Day. Enjoy the fireworks!
No better way to start the day in Southwestern Wisconsin than with a stop at Kickapoo Coffee in Viroqua, WI. Great local business with delicious food and coffee!
Throughout week Team Kind is holding open office hours in all 18 counties in Wisconsin‚Äôs Third Congressional District. Hope you are able to stop by. Click below to find your local hours.
It is the stories of Wisconsinites, like this family from Jackson County, that remind me why we must work every day to make sure that access to affordable, quality health care is protected.

Planning to take a road trip this summer? Check out The Great River Road that stretches over 3,000 miles and goes through ten states following the Mississippi River from St. Croix to the Gulf of Mexico!

Today, the House passed my bill to make it easier for families, like the Poluda's of Eau Claire, to obtain their loved ones replacement service medals when the original medals have been lost.  The Honoring Our Heroes Act was inspired by Tari Poulda, whose great uncle, Bruce Bradley, died during the Pearl Harbor attacks on the USS Arizona.  Though Bradley (S2.c, USN) and his family received a posthumous Purple Heart, the medal had been misplaced in the early 2000s.  With Tari‚Äôs help and determination, we worked together to ensure no other family is denied their loved ones service medals simply because of an arbitrary rule.

One of my favorite parts of the week is getting to talk with Wisconsinites visiting our Nation's Capitol about how we can partner with them to find solutions to the problems our local communities are dealing with.
It is time we put solutions over politics and come together to recognize what works in healthcare, fix what doesn‚Äôt, and seek to lower healthcare costs for all Americans.

Hope everyone is staying safe after the severe storms in western Wisconsin. If you are looking to find the best person to contact or have a question about how to report damage please call my office at 608-782-2558.   Please be sure to check for road closures before you head out on the roads.
Beat the heat at a Wisconsin County fair this summer. It's fun for the whole family!
Shameful! Today the Senate voted to debate a #healthcare bill that they have no idea the contents of. Wisconsin deserves better.

Over the last six months, Wisconsinites have faced far too much uncertainty when it comes to their health care. We can‚Äôt let the uncertainty continue, which is why I am calling on Congress to stay in session during August to provide certainty and stabilize the health insurance markets. It is time to work together and recognize what works in health care, fix what doesn‚Äôt, and lower health care costs for all Americans.

Wisconsinites want solutions, not party politics.  It‚Äôs time to work together to repair and fix Obamacare, so Wisconsin families continue to have dependable and secure healthcare.   My plan to improve healthcare is:  1) Stabilize health insurance markets 2) Reduce costs for individuals and small businesses 3) Address rising prescription drug prices 4) Continue payment and delivery system reforms  Thank you Independent Living Resources of La Crosse and others for working with me to make sure Wisconsinites have access to affordable, quality healthcare.

Yesterday, I joined Fire Chief Bob Finn in celebrating the Stevens Point Fire Department's recently awarded $98,000 grant from FEMA, which helped them buy six LUCAS mechanical CPR machines. This week, I joined Wisconsinites and Minnesotans in St. Croix  and Washington County in celebrating the new St. Croix River Bridge. The new bridge is the product of decades-long hard work and cooperation, and I was proud to see communities on both sides of the river come together to celebrate.

While in Menomonie I had the honor of recognizing Civil Air Patrol Cadet Casey Owen for earning his Bronze and Silver Congressional Awards. Today I had a great morning on the Koller family farm in Mondovi talking with local farmers about the challenges they face, and how we can work together to craft a Farm Bill that supports their families and grows our local rural economy.

Thank you to everyone in Pepin and Buffalo counties that joined me at my listening sessions yesterday. Hearing from Wisconsinites about the issues that matter most to them is my favorite part of this job.

As a proud kid from the Northside of La Crosse, I‚Äôm happy to see the Roosevelt School building being put to good use. Yesterday, I joined the Boys & Girls Clubs of Greater La Crosse in celebrating their recently awarded ‚ÄúBe Great: Graduate‚Äù grant from AT&T. I look forward to watching the Club continue to help the community by helping students stay on track to graduate high school.

Congratulations to Jacob Leinenkugel Brewing Co. on 150 years of great beer and great business in Wisconsin! This week, I toured GoMacro in Viola. Amelia, Tony, and the Go Macro folks showed me around the factory and farm, and we discussed what it takes to grow a family business into a nation-wide success.

Today, I co-sponsored a resolution urging the US Postal Service to continue 6-day mail delivery. Though Bradley (S2.c, USN) and his family received a posthumous Purple Heart, the medal had been misplaced in the early 2000s.

With Veterans Day approaching I want to thank you for your service to our country and invite you to attend a Veterans Town Hall I am holding on Friday, November 10th in La Crosse.  We can enjoy the freedoms we have because of the brave men and women who have sacrificed to keep us safe. However, many people fail to realize the struggle many of our service members go through when transitioning back to civilian life.  On this Veterans Day I wanted to give Wisconsin veterans the opportunity to hear from other veterans or share your own story about the challenges of rejoining civilian life. Please find details on the Veterans Day Town Hall below.  La Crosse Veterans Town Hall Friday, November 10th 1:00 pm American Legion Post 52  711 6th St S, La Crosse, Wisconsin 54601  The personal stories of America‚Äôs veterans are the most powerful record that we have to document the sacrifice and hardship of our nation at war. If you are a veteran and would like to speak, email or call my veterans liaison Mark Aumann, at mark.aumann@mail.house.gov or 715-831-9214. Please do not hesitate to contact my office if have any questions.  Look forward to seeing you there,  Ron Kind
